---
// jet lag + shift work — CONTEXT page (CHK-5.2, PR-B). NOT a graded remedy and NOT advice about what to
// take: it's context on why jet lag and shift work are CIRCADIAN (clock-timing) problems, not sedation
// problems — so melatonin's evidence here is about TIMING, not sedating you through a night — and why
// shift-work sleep problems are a clinician conversation, not a self-treat. No tier badge, no
// evidence-gate chips, no plannedTier. Mirrors medications-and-sleep-aids.astro structure exactly. Every
// specific is cited to a source verified firsthand:
//   1 Herxheimer & Petrie, Cochrane 2002 — 10 RCTs; in 9, melatonin taken close to the traveller's target
//     bedtime at the DESTINATION reduced jet lag after flights crossing 5+ time zones (larger effect
//     eastward); daily 0.5–5 mg similarly effective; taken at the WRONG time (early in the day) it could
//     cause sleepiness and delay adaptation. The anchor NEW cite. PMID 12076414 / DOI 10.1002/14651858.CD001520.
//   2 Auger et al. AASM 2015 (reused from corpus) — clinical practice guideline for INTRINSIC circadian
//     rhythm sleep-wake disorders: conditional endorsement of strategically TIMED melatonin for DSWPD and
//     for blind adults with N24SWD. NOTE (verified firsthand): it does NOT endorse melatonin for shift
//     work disorder — so shift work stays routed to a clinician. PMID 26414986 / DOI 10.5664/jcsm.5100.
// Shift-work disorder itself is kept NAVIGATIONAL (route to a clinician / when-to-see-a-doctor); no
// clean melatonin-for-SWD endorsement exists, so none is cited. Drowsy-driving is a safety boundary, not
// a cited statistic.
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import ContextBanner from '../components/ContextBanner.astro';
import ContextSources from '../components/ContextSources.astro';
import Disclaimer from '../components/Disclaimer.astro';
import Fn from '../components/Fn.astro';

const sources = [
  {
    n: 1,
    cite: 'Herxheimer A, Petrie KJ. Melatonin for the prevention and treatment of jet lag. Cochrane Database Syst Rev. 2002;(2):CD001520.',
    finding:
      'Cochrane systematic review of ten randomised trials: in nine of them, melatonin taken close to the traveller’s target bedtime at the destination (about 10pm–midnight) reduced jet lag after flights crossing five or more time zones, with a larger effect for eastward travel; daily doses between 0.5 and 5 mg were similarly effective; and taken at the wrong time — early in the destination day — melatonin could cause sleepiness and delay adaptation, making clear the effect is about timing, not sedation.',
    pmid: '12076414',
    doi: '10.1002/14651858.CD001520',
  },
  {
    n: 2,
    cite: 'Auger RR, Burgess HJ, Emens JS, Deriy LV, Thomas SM, Sharkey KM. Clinical Practice Guideline for the Treatment of Intrinsic Circadian Rhythm Sleep-Wake Disorders (AASM). J Clin Sleep Med. 2015;11(10):1199–1236.',
    finding:
      'American Academy of Sleep Medicine clinical practice guideline for intrinsic circadian rhythm sleep-wake disorders: it gives a conditional endorsement of strategically TIMED melatonin for delayed sleep-wake phase disorder and for blind adults with non-24-hour disorder — melatonin used as a scheduled clock signal under clinical guidance, not a nightly sedative — and it does NOT endorse melatonin for shift work disorder.',
    pmid: '26414986',
    doi: '10.5664/jcsm.5100',
  },
];
---

<Base
  title="jet lag + shift work: a clock problem, not a sedation problem | Somnary"
  description="jet lag and shift work are circadian problems — your internal clock is out of step with the world's — so melatonin's evidence here is about timing, not sedating you to sleep. and shift-work sleep problems are a clinician conversation, not a self-treat. context on that distinction — not a grade, and not advice about what to take."
  canonical="https://somnary.vercel.app/jet-lag-shift-work"
>
  <main class="page">
    <header class="head">
      <p class="eyebrow">context · circadian rhythm</p>
      <h1 class="title">jet lag + shift work<span class="dot">.</span></h1>
      <p class="dek">
        Jet lag and shift work are <em>circadian</em> problems: your internal clock is out of step
        with the world around you, not simply a matter of not being sleepy enough. That's why
        melatonin's evidence here is about <em>timing</em> — nudging the clock — rather than sedating
        you to sleep, and why persistent shift-work sleep trouble is a clinician conversation rather
        than something to self-treat. This page is context on that distinction — it is not a grade, and
        it does not tell you what to take or what is safe for you.
      </p>
    </header>

    <ContextBanner
      note="matching your clock to a new time zone or a night-shift schedule is a timing problem specific to your situation. this page describes what the circadian evidence documents, and routes shift-work sleep problems to a clinician."
    />

    <p class="who">
      <span class="who-tag">who this is for</span>
      travellers crossing several time zones, and people working night or rotating shifts, who are
      weighing melatonin — or wondering why ordinary sleep advice isn't fixing the problem.
    </p>

    <!-- safety boundary: don't self-treat shift-work disorder + don't drive drowsy (serious) -->
    <section class="callout sev-serious" role="note" aria-label="shift-work and drowsy-driving hazard">
      <div class="callout-head">
        <span class="sigil" aria-hidden="true">!</span>
        <p class="callout-title">don't self-treat shift-work disorder, and never drive drowsy</p>
      </div>
      <p class="callout-body">
        Persistent trouble sleeping or staying awake around night or rotating shifts can be
        <strong>shift work disorder</strong> — a recognised circadian rhythm sleep-wake disorder that
        belongs with a clinician who can assess it, not a supplement picked off a shelf. And the
        sleepiness that comes with a disrupted clock is dangerous behind the wheel: <strong>drowsy
        driving</strong> is a serious hazard, and no sleep aid removes it — if you are fighting to stay
        awake, do not drive. Melatonin's evidence here is about shifting the clock's timing, not
        sedating you through a shift, and it is not a treatment for a disorder. If shift work is
        wrecking your sleep, that is a <a href="/when-to-see-a-doctor">clinician conversation</a>, not
        a self-assembled fix.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- section 01: what people assume -->
    <section class="section">
      <p class="eyebrow">section 01</p>
      <h2 class="section-title">what people assume</h2>
      <div class="prose">
        <p>
          The usual assumption is that jet lag and shift-work exhaustion are just tiredness — that the
          fix is anything that makes you sleepy at the right moment. So melatonin gets reached for like
          a sedative, and shift workers try to power through with the same tricks that work for an
          ordinary late night. The framing this page pushes back on is that these are <em>clock</em>
          problems: the issue isn't a shortage of sleepiness, it's that your internal timing is
          pointing at the wrong hour — and a sedative doesn't move a clock.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- section 02: what's actually documented -->
    <section class="section">
      <p class="eyebrow">section 02</p>
      <h2 class="section-title">what's actually documented</h2>
      <div class="prose">
        <p>
          For jet lag specifically, the evidence is unusually clear. A Cochrane review of ten
          randomised trials found that in <strong>nine</strong> of them, melatonin taken close to the
          traveller's target bedtime at the destination reduced jet lag after flights crossing
          <strong>five or more time zones</strong>, with a larger effect for eastward travel; daily
          doses between <strong>0.5 and 5 mg</strong> were similarly effective.<Fn n={1} /> The same
          review makes the timing point sharply: taken at the wrong time — early in the destination day
          — melatonin could <em>cause</em> sleepiness and delay adaptation.<Fn n={1} /> That is the
          mechanism in one sentence: this is a timing signal, and the timing is what matters.
        </p>
        <p>
          For the intrinsic clock disorders it covers, an AASM clinical practice guideline likewise
          gives a conditional endorsement of strategically <strong>timed</strong> melatonin — for
          delayed sleep-wake phase disorder, and for blind adults with non-24-hour disorder — again as
          a scheduled clock signal under clinical guidance, not a nightly sedative.<Fn n={2} /> Notably,
          that guideline covers only these intrinsic clock disorders; <strong>shift work
          disorder</strong> falls outside its scope — one reason shift work sits on the clinician side
          of the line.<Fn n={2} />
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- section 03: what these findings do NOT show -->
    <section class="section">
      <p class="eyebrow">section 03</p>
      <h2 class="section-title">what these findings do <em>not</em> show</h2>
      <div class="prose">
        <p>
          The jet-lag evidence describes what happened in trials of travellers; it doesn't tell you
          what to take, when, or whether melatonin fits your health and medicines. &ldquo;Similarly
          effective across 0.5 to 5 mg&rdquo; is a finding about trial averages, not a dose
          instruction, and effectiveness for jet lag says nothing about safety alongside your other
          medications or conditions.<Fn n={1} /> The circadian-disorder guidance is for specific
          disorders diagnosed and assessed by a clinician — not a green light to self-diagnose.<Fn n={2} />
          And the clearest gap is shift work: the evidence base is thinner, that circadian-disorder
          guideline doesn't cover it, and shift work disorder itself needs professional assessment. None of
          this diagnoses your sleep problem or ranks your options for you.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- section 04: dose / form / timing reality -->
    <section class="section">
      <p class="eyebrow">section 04</p>
      <h2 class="section-title">dose, form &amp; timing reality</h2>
      <div class="prose">
        <p>
          Timing is the active ingredient here, which makes it the easy thing to get wrong — the same
          milligrams that help when aligned to a destination night can backfire taken at the wrong
          hour.<Fn n={1} /> In the jet-lag trials, travellers took melatonin close to bedtime at the
          destination; the guideline use for clock disorders is scheduled to a person's specific rhythm
          under guidance.<Fn n={1} /><Fn n={2} /> This page describes what those studies and guidelines
          used — it is not a schedule for you to follow. <a href="/melatonin-dose-timing">melatonin
          dose &amp; timing</a> covers the trial doses and timing in detail, and for a night-shift or
          rotating pattern the right approach depends on your schedule and health in ways only a
          clinician can map.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- section 05: take these to a clinician or pharmacist -->
    <section class="section">
      <p class="eyebrow">section 05</p>
      <h2 class="section-title">take these to a clinician or pharmacist</h2>
      <ul class="ask">
        <li>is my sleep problem jet lag that will pass, or a shift-related pattern that should be assessed?</li>
        <li>could this be shift work disorder, and what evaluation would tell us?</li>
        <li>if melatonin is considered for timing, when — relative to my schedule — was it actually studied, and does it fit my medicines and conditions?</li>
        <li>how do I manage sleepiness safely around driving and work while my clock is disrupted?</li>
        <li>what non-drug steps, such as light exposure and schedule, fit my situation?</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <!-- related: the timing detail + the graded hub + the primary boundary -->
    <section class="section">
      <p class="eyebrow">related</p>
      <h2 class="section-title">read next</h2>
      <ul class="related">
        <li><a href="/melatonin-dose-timing">melatonin dose &amp; timing</a> — what dose and timing the circadian trials actually used.</li>
        <li><a href="/r/melatonin">melatonin</a> — the full evidence grade and what the trials found.</li>
        <li><a href="/safety">safety &amp; interactions</a> — the primary boundary: how Somnary handles interactions and when to route to a clinician.</li>
        <li><a href="/when-to-see-a-doctor">when to see a doctor</a> — the signs that disrupted sleep needs evaluation, not a supplement.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <ContextSources sources={sources} />

    <div class="disclaimer-slot">
      <Disclaimer variant="standard" />
    </div>

    <p class="review-line">
      reviewed 2026-07-08 · found an error? <a href="/methodology#corrections">corrections →</a>
    </p>
  </main>
</Base>

